sectionBreak.stem:
As shown in the figure below, water enters a cylindrical tank at a constant flow rate Qin and fills until the water reaches yhigh.

 

%media:23.001.1.jpg%

 

At this point, water siphons out of the tank through a circular discharge pipe, producing a fountain at the pipe’s exit. The fountain runs until the water level decreases to ylow, whereupon the siphon fills with air and the fountain stops. The cycle then repeats as the tank fills until the water reaches yhigh, and the fountain flows again. When the siphon is running, the outflow Qout can be computed with the following formula based on Torricelli’s law:

 

%media:formula107.mml%

 

Neglect the volume of water in the pipe and assume the initial condition of an empty tank y(0) = 0.  Form a mathematical model for the flow of water.

Given:

RT = 0.05 m        r = 0.007 m        ylow = 0.025 m              

yhigh = 0.1 m      C = 0.6            g = 9.81 m/s2

Qin = 50 × 10–6 m3/s

worksheet.stem:
Find the value of the definite integral of the given function between x = 0 and 1 using the ode45 function. (Round the final answer to five decimal places.)

 

The value of the definite integral = __a__.
worksheet.commonFeedback:
Using ode45 is based on recognizing that the evaluation of the definite integral

 

%media:formula47.mml%

 

is equivalent to solving the differential equation given below for y(b) with the initial condition y(a) = 0.

 

%media:formula48.mml%

 

Thus, we must solve the following initial-value problem:

 

%media:formula49.mml%

 

where y(0) = 0. To do this with ode45, first set up an M-file to evaluate the right-hand side of the differential equation.

 

function dy = humpsODE(x,y)
dy = 1./((x-0.3).^2 + 0.01) + 1./((x-0.9).^2+0.04) - 6;

 

Then, the integral can be evaluated as

 

>> [x,y] = ode45(@humpsODE,[0 0.5 1],0);
>> disp([x,y])
                 0                    0
  0.50000000000000    21.78356481821654
  1.00000000000000    29.85525185285369

 

Thus, the integral estimate is within 0.01% of the estimate obtained with the quad function. Note that a better estimate can be obtained by using the odeset function to set a smaller relative tolerance.

 

>> options = odeset('RelTol',1e-8);
>> [x,y] = ode45(@humpsODE,[0 0.5 1],0,options);
>> disp([x,y])
                 0                    0
  0.50000000000000    21.78683736423308
  1.00000000000000    29.85832514287622

hint.name: hint #1
hint.value: What is the formula for resonant frequency?

worksheet.stem:
Find the system’s resonant frequencies using the developed M-file. (Round the final answers to four decimal places and enter the values in increasing order of frequencies.)

 

The system’s resonant frequencies = __a__Hz and __b__Hz.
worksheet.commonFeedback:
The following function can be used to hold the ODEs:

 

function dx = dxdtProb2320(t,x,k1,k2,m1,m2,w1,w2,L1,L2)
dx = [x(3);x(4);-k1/m1*(x(1)-L1)+k2/m1*(x(2)-x(1)-w1-L2); ...
-k2/m2*(x(2)-x(1)-w1-L2)];

 

The following script employs the ode45 function to generate the solution and then generates the power spectrum for the first mass’s displacement:

 

clear,clf,clc
k1=5;k2=5;m1=2;m2=2;w1=5;w2=5;L1=2;L2=2;
[t,x]=ode45(@dxdtProb2320,[0:1/16:32],[2 15 0 0],[],k1,k2,m1,m2,w1,w2,L1,L2);
subplot(2,1,1);plot(t,x(:,1))
grid;title('(a) Displacement of first mass')
n=length(t)-1; dt=(max(t)-min(t))/n;fs=1/dt;nyquist=fs/2;
Y=fft(x(:,1))/n;
Y(1)=[];
% compute and display the power spectrum
f = (1:n/2)/(n/2)*nyquist;
Pyy = abs(Y(1:n/2)).^2;
subplot(2,1,2);
bar(f,Pyy)
title('(b) Power spectrum')
xlabel('Frequency (Hz)');

 

The power spectrum indicates peaks at 0.1563 and 0.4063 Hz. This result can be validated by determining the systems eigenvalues:

 

A=[k1/m1+k2/m1 -k2/m1;-k2/m2 k2/m2];
lambda=eig(A);
freq=sqrt(lambda)/(2*pi)


freq =
     0.1555
     0.4072

worksheet.stem:
Find the system’s resonant frequencies using an M-file. (Round the final answers to four decimal places and enter the values in decreasing order.)

 

The system’s resonant frequencies in increasing order are __a__Hz, __b__Hz, and __c__Hz.
worksheet.commonFeedback:
The following function can be used to hold the ODEs:

 

function dx = dxdtProb2321(t,x,m1,m2,m3,k1,k2,k3)
dx=[x(4);x(5);x(6);-k1/m1*x(1)+k2/m1*(x(2)-x(1)); ...
   k2/m2*(x(1)-x(2))+k3/m2*(x(3)-x(2)); ...
   k3/m3*(x(2)-x(3))];

 

The following script employs the ode45 function to generate the solution and then generates the power spectrum for the floor’s displacement:

 

clear,clf,clc
m1=12000;m2=10000;m3=8000;
k1=3000;k2=2400;k3=1800;
tspan=[0:1/8:128];y0=[0 0 0 1 0 0];
[t,x]=ode45(@dxdtProb2321,tspan,y0,[],m1,m2,m3,k1,k2,k3);
subplot(2,1,1);plot(t,x(:,1))
xlabel('time (s)');ylabel('displacement (m)');
grid;title('(a) Displacement of first floor')
n=length(t)-1; dt=(max(t)-min(t))/n;fs=1/dt;nyquist=fs/2;
Y=fft(x(:,1))/n;
Y(1)=[];
% compute and display the power spectrum
f = (1:n/2)/(n/2)*nyquist;
Pyy = abs(Y(1:n/2)).^2;
subplot(2,1,2);
bar(f(1:n/32),Pyy(1:n/32))
title('(b) Power spectrum')
xlabel('Frequency (Hz)');
% Use eigenvalues to determine fundamental frequencies

 

The power spectrum indicates peaks at 0.0390625, 0.09375, and 0.1328125 Hz. This result can be validated by determining the system's eigenvalues:

 

A=[(k1+k2)/m1 -k2/m1 0; ...
-k2/m2 (k2+k3)/m2 -k3/m2; ...
0 -k3/m3 k3/m3];
lambda=eig(A);
freq=sqrt(lambda)/(2*pi)


freq =
     0.1330
     0.0927
     0.0380

where x = distance (m), t = time (s), v = velocity (m/s) where positive velocity is in the downward direction, g = the acceleration of gravity (= 9.81 m/s2), cd = a second-order drag coefficient = 0.25 (kg/m), and m = mass = 68.1 (kg). Note that in this formulation, distance and velocity are both positive in the downward direction, and the ground level is defined as zero distance.

 

Assume that the jumper is initially located 200 m above the ground and the initial velocity is 20 m/s in the upward direction—that is, x(0) = –200 and v(0) = –20.

worksheet.stem:
Find the time, height, and velocity when the bungee jumper is the farthest above the ground using the given equation. (Round the final answers to four decimal places.)

 

 Time = __a__s

Height = __b__ m

Velocity = __c__ m/s
worksheet.commonFeedback:
Script:

 

clear,clc,clf
opts=odeset('events',@endevent2322);
y0=[-200 -20];
[t,y,te,ye]=ode45(@freefall,[0 inf],y0,opts,0.25,68.1);
te,ye
subplot(2,1,1)
plot(t,-y(:,1),'LineWidth',2)
title('height (m)')
ylabel('x (m)'),grid
subplot(2,1,2)
plot(t,-y(:,2),'LineWidth',2)
title('velocity (m/s)')
xlabel('time (s)');ylabel('v (m/s)'),grid

 

Supporting functions:

 

function dydt=freefall(t,y,cd,m)
% y(1) = x and y(2) = v
grav=9.81;
dydt=[y(2);grav-cd/m*y(2)*abs(y(2))];
function [detect,stopint,direction]=endevent2322(t,y,varargin)
% Locate the time when velocity is zero at maximum
% and stop integration.
detect=y(2); % Detect height = 0
stopint=1; % Stop the integration
direction=0; % Direction does not matter
